 To Porch Fort Worth, our friends just down the way.

28
00:01:54,000 --> 00:01:59,000
 We love you guys. Porch Midland, our other friends just a little further west of us here.

29
00:01:59,000 --> 00:02:04,000
 And then Porch Springfield. We love that we get to tune in together.

30
00:02:04,000 --> 00:02:12,000
 Well, I've never been skydiving, but over the summer I got the chance to try the next best alternative.

31
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:16,000
 I went indoor skydiving. Anybody been indoor skydiving before?

32
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:20,000
 It is far less superior to the real thing, I would imagine.

33
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:27,000
 And yet, there are a couple of distinct advantages to indoor skydiving to that of outdoor skydiving.

34
00:02:27,000 --> 00:02:37,000
 I know this because I asked our instructor, who was apparently goaded as the skydiving expert in our beloved city of Dallas, Texas.

35
00:02:37,000 --> 00:02:48,000
 The advantages are this. Number one, when you indoor skydive, you actually get a longer free fall experience than you do when you're outdoor.

36
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:55,000
 The reason why is when you're outdoor, it's estimated that 30 to 60 seconds of your time is actually spent in free fall.

37
00:02:55,000 --> 00:02:59,000
 And then of course you get to slowly float your way to the ground.

38
00:02:59,000 --> 00:03:03,000
 If not, then something terribly tragic has happened to you.

39
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:08,000
 When you go indoor, you actually get 90 seconds of total time, which is awesome.

40
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:12,000
 I'm sure they'll give you more. You just have to pay for that. That's the first advantage.

41
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:20,000
 The second advantage is you actually get to fly solo, which is awesome.

42
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:26,000
 Because it means that you don't have a full adult grown man attached to your back.

43
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:30,000
 And traversing through the skies, you both fall to your inevitable doom.

44
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:37,000
 You get to free fall by yourself. You get to fly all alone.

45
00:03:37,000 --> 00:03:44,000
 And so I'm pumped for it. We show up. We get all of our gear and we're making our way in line.

46
00:03:44,000 --> 00:03:52,000
 And as we're watching the group in front of us kind of go through all the motions of free falling, we're standing there killing a little bit of a moment.

47
00:03:52,000 --> 00:03:56,000
 I look over to our instructor and I just ask him, trying to be kind, make conversation.

48
00:03:56,000 --> 00:04:01,000
 But he's also goaded, so maybe he's got something that can help me. And I just simply ask the question,

49
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:04,000
 "Hey, any final advice for a future free faller?"

50
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:09,000
 He looks at me and he says something that has stuck with me to this day.

51
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:14,000
 He said, "What you feel determines how you fly."

52
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:21,000
 So if you feel yourself sinking, then open up your body, spread your hands, lift your chin.

53
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:28,000
 If you feel yourself drifting one direction, then turn your hands the opposite and let it pull you back the other way.

54
00:04:28,000 --> 00:04:35,000
 Ultimately, though, know this, whatever you do, don't fight the wind. Just feel it.

55
00:04:35,000 --> 00:04:43,000
 And he was right. As I did these things, my experience, which was unlike anything I had ever experienced before, was amazing.

56
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:46,000
 Like I found myself in a situation that I had never encountered.

57
00:04:46,000 --> 00:04:55,000
 One where the wind was rushing in this tunnel and I could feel the deafening noise and my heart was pounding in my chest.

58
00:04:55,000 --> 00:05:02,000
 And yet in the midst of it all, I knew so long as I could feel the wind, I wouldn't fall flat on my face.

59
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:05,000
 I could actually fly through the air.

60
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:10,000
 Now, why do I tell you that? Because I think his advice is not just good advice for free falling.

61
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:13,000
 I think it's good advice for you and me.

62
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:20,000
 And the reason why is we're going to similarly find ourselves in moments where we're encountering something the likes of which we've never experienced.

63
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:26,000
 We're going to be put in a proverbial wind tunnel and they're going to crank up the engine and things are going to get crazy.

64
00:05:26,000 --> 00:05:35,000
 And what we choose to do in that moment, how we respond to whatever we feel, how we process our emotion,

65
00:05:35,000 --> 00:05:42,000
 is going to determine whether we fall flat on our face or we actually fly through the air.

66
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:47,000
 You see, you've got to know how to process the things that are happening inside.

67
00:05:47,000 --> 00:05:51,000
 And while that seems obvious, human beings are notoriously bad at this.

68
00:05:51,000 --> 00:05:59,000
 Christians are especially bad at processing what we feel because what we do is we find ourselves kind of camped in one of two extreme categories.

69
00:05:59,000 --> 00:06:02,000
 We're either all head and no heart or we're the alternative.

70
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:07,000
 So for those of you in the room that are all head and no heart, you know what's right.

71
00:06:07,000 --> 00:06:09,000
 And so you do what's right.

72
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:16,000
 And even when what's right doesn't feel right, you do it anyways, because right is right and wrong is wrong and that is that.

73
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:18,000
 You know, it doesn't matter if you feel an alternative way.

74
00:06:18,000 --> 00:06:22,000
 You take those feelings and you stuff them very deeply down inside.

75
00:06:22,000 --> 00:06:25,000
 You suppress them in a way where you never acknowledge them.

76
00:06:25,000 --> 00:06:27,000
 You lock them away. You throw away the key.

77
00:06:27,000 --> 00:06:29,000
 You don't recognize your feelings.

78
00:06:29,000 --> 00:06:32,000
 You refuse them all together.

79
00:06:32,000 --> 00:06:37,000
 This is some people's approach whenever their emotions come into play.

80
00:06:37,000 --> 00:06:40,000
 But for others, they're not all head and no heart.

81
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:43,000
 They're all heart and no head.

82
00:06:43,000 --> 00:06:47,000
 Rather than suppressing their feelings, they become possessed by them.

83
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:51,000
 So much so that when they catch feelings for that guy or that girl, it's all they can think about.

84
00:06:51,000 --> 00:06:52,000
 It's all they can talk about.

85
00:06:52,000 --> 00:06:55,000
 It doesn't matter if you're their friend and you have something else that you would like to discuss.

86
00:06:55,000 --> 00:06:58,000
 That's what they're going to talk to you about.

87
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:01,000
 If you find yourself cut off in traffic, you know who you are.

88
00:07:01,000 --> 00:07:04,000
 You wage war against the entire interstate.

89
00:07:04,000 --> 00:07:07,000
 Because one passerby chose to take an issue with you.

90
00:07:07,000 --> 00:07:09,000
 You know, like that's your approach.

91
00:07:09,000 --> 00:07:11,000
 You're possessed. You're consumed.

92
00:07:11,000 --> 00:07:15,000
 You're overwhelmed by what you feel.

93
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:18,000
 By and large, we go one way or the other.

94
00:07:18,000 --> 00:07:20,000
 But what if there was a third option?

95
00:07:20,000 --> 00:07:24,000
 Like what if you didn't have to go all head or all heart?

96
00:07:24,000 --> 00:07:28,000
 What if you could actually be both at the same time?

97
00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:30,000
 Well, that's the option that the Bible gives us.

98
00:07:30,000 --> 00:07:36,000
 It wants to teach us a different, a better way to process what we feel.

99
00:07:36,000 --> 00:07:42,000
 To not ignore what we feel and to not enable what we feel, but to inform what we feel.

100
00:07:42,000 --> 00:07:46,000
 To inform it with God's truth.

101
00:07:46,000 --> 00:07:55,000
 You see, as we read the Word, what we find is that we should feel all of our feelings.

102
00:07:55,000 --> 00:07:58,000
 And then we bring them under submission to God's Word.

103
00:07:58,000 --> 00:08:02,000
 We let Him tell us how we process those things.

104
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:04,000
 And as we do, something amazing happens.

105
00:08:04,000 --> 00:08:08,000
 What we find is our anxiety turns into peace.

106
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:12,000
 Our fear becomes trust. Our anger becomes patience.

107
00:08:12,000 --> 00:08:19,000
 We engage a kind of spirituality that forms not just what we know, but really who we are.

108
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:23,000
 Which is exactly what young adults, people just like you, are wanting.

109
00:08:23,000 --> 00:08:26,000
 According to Barna, when asked this question,

110
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:30,000
 "What are you looking for when you consider your spiritual beliefs?"

111
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:35,000
 Young adults, out of 10 different options, all of which were really compelling,

112
00:08:35,000 --> 00:08:40,000
 they selected these three as their greatest desire.

113
00:08:40,000 --> 00:08:50,000
 They selected inner peace, hope, and healing as the fruit of that which they wanted to be true in their spiritual experience.

114
00:08:50,000 --> 00:08:55,000
 Which is massive. I don't know if it clicks for you why it's such a big deal.

115
00:08:55,000 --> 00:09:00,000
 But what that's telling us is we want a spirituality that doesn't just change what we do,

116
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:02,000
 as much as it changes who we are.

117
00:09:02,000 --> 00:09:06,000
 That impacts us at a core, internal level.

118
00:09:06,000 --> 00:09:08,000
 That can fix what's gone wrong.

119
00:09:08,000 --> 00:09:09,000
 That can heal what's been hurt.

120
00:09:09,000 --> 00:09:15,000
 That can mend the parts of you that feel unmendable.

121
00:09:15,000 --> 00:09:23,000
 What this also does is it strikes, at least me, maybe you, with a really surprising notion.

122
00:09:23,000 --> 00:09:31,000
 That our current reality is not giving us the tools or the solutions we need to actually change who we are.

123
00:09:31,000 --> 00:09:37,000
 You see, it's surprising because we live in the most therapized era in human history.

124
00:09:37,000 --> 00:09:42,000
 You see, never before has the conversation around mental health been more destigmatized than right now.

125
00:09:42,000 --> 00:09:47,000
 So much so that people are using therapy language in everyday regular speech.

126
00:09:47,000 --> 00:09:54,000
 We were recently visiting with a girl and she was telling us that she's falling head over heels for this guy,

127
00:09:54,000 --> 00:10:01,000
 but she's not sure if it's a legitimate feeling or if it's just the result of some trauma bonding they had as they were fighting traffic at the state fair.

128
00:10:01,000 --> 00:10:10,000
 I don't necessarily know if traffic qualifies for trauma bonding, but I have my suspicions that it doesn't.

129
00:10:10,000 --> 00:10:15,000
 You see, we have adopted mental health language in our regular conversations.

130
00:10:15,000 --> 00:10:28,000
 We say things like toxic and trauma and manic and OCD and emotional attachment or anxious attachment or codependency or gaslighting in everyday normal conversation.

131
00:10:28,000 --> 00:10:35,000
 And it's telling us that we live in a moment in history where mental health is more accepted than ever before.

132
00:10:35,000 --> 00:10:47,000
 But, and this is big, we are nonetheless the most anxious, depressed, and lonely generation that has ever been recorded.

133
00:10:47,000 --> 00:10:51,000
 Isn't that interesting?

134
00:10:51,000 --> 00:10:54,000
 Now, is that telling us that therapy is bad?

135
00:10:54,000 --> 00:10:56,000
 No, of course not.

136
00:10:56,000 --> 00:11:00,000
 Correlation does not equal causation, not in every instance.

137
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:05,000
 It's not saying that therapy is bad, but it is telling us that therapy isn't enough.

138
00:11:05,000 --> 00:11:11,000
 What we need to shape our perspective of reality is more than just worldly wisdom.

139
00:11:11,000 --> 00:11:13,000
 We need God's truth.

140
00:11:13,000 --> 00:11:17,000
 We need his word, which is what this entire series is about.

141
00:11:17,000 --> 00:11:22,000
 Over the course of the next several weeks, we want to help bring your mental health into proper perspective.

142
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:25,000
 And to do it, we thought we would work through the book of Psalms.

143
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:33,000
 The reason why is the book of Psalms is the best teacher on how to feel all of your feelings and then bring those things to God.

144
00:11:33,000 --> 00:11:41,000
 I don't know if you've read them before, but it is characteristically normal to look at the Psalms and see David is freaking out over something.

145
00:11:41,000 --> 00:11:50,000
 And yet by the end of the Psalm, he is presenting his requests to God and he is changing at his inmost level.

146
00:11:50,000 --> 00:11:56,000
 We think the Psalms will be informative for us as we engage this specific topic for that reason.

147
00:11:56,000 --> 00:12:03,000
 You see, it teaches us to not stuff our feelings away, but to address our feelings with God's truth.

148
00:12:03,000 --> 00:12:11,000
 And just to kick off the series, what seemed most plausible was for us to just start with that mental health disorder that is most common in our country.

149
00:12:11,000 --> 00:12:13,000
 Depression.

150
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:30,000
 According to the American Psychological Association, depression is a negative affective state ranging from unhappiness and discontent to an extreme feeling of sadness, pessimism, and despondency that interferes with daily life.

151
00:12:30,000 --> 00:12:33,000
 You see, that tells us something really important about depression.

152
00:12:33,000 --> 00:12:48,000
 It tells us that there is a continuum that we need to consider where on one end you have general discouragement and on the other you have very personal despair.

153
00:12:48,000 --> 00:12:57,000
 And the reason why it's important for us to consider that continuum is in a room this size with this many people, including all of those that are tuning in online or watching this later,

154
00:12:57,000 --> 00:13:05,000
 we all can more than likely find ourselves, if not right now, at some point on the range of those possibilities.

155
00:13:05,000 --> 00:13:07,000
 I know that was the case for me.

156
00:13:07,000 --> 00:13:14,000
 I never thought in my own life that I would be depressed, and yet I found myself having lived through some specific hardships,

157
00:13:14,000 --> 00:13:21,000
 being forced into a counselor's office, and kind of processing through all the circumstantial difficulties I had lived through.

158
00:13:21,000 --> 00:13:27,000
 And as a result of that experience, I found out that I was situationally depressed.

159
00:13:27,000 --> 00:13:32,000
 And it was paradigm shifting for me in that season.

160
00:13:32,000 --> 00:13:40,000
 It changed things in a way where it gave some explanation to why I was the way I was, why I was thinking the way I was thinking, why I was feeling the way I was feeling.

161
00:13:40,000 --> 00:13:46,000
 It helped me to understand, man, this makes sense, why I'm insecure about my job, or why I'm irritable in my marriage,

162
00:13:46,000 --> 00:13:52,000
 or why I find myself indifferent about the things that I used to love to enjoy.

163
00:13:52,000 --> 00:13:54,000
 I'm situationally depressed.

164
00:13:54,000 --> 00:14:00,000
 And as I began to process that experience, I would talk to my counselor, who's a biblical counselor,

165
00:14:00,000 --> 00:14:05,000
 and she would inform me that I needed to spend some time in the Psalms.

166
00:14:05,000 --> 00:14:10,000
 And those Psalms, they minister to me in a deep way because this is what the Psalms are useful for.

167
00:14:10,000 --> 00:14:16,000
 They're useful for explaining our emotion and bringing those things to God's truth and helping form us into new people.

168
00:14:16,000 --> 00:14:24,000
 Psalm 42 was particularly helpful for me, which is why I want to look at it with you tonight as we talk about depression.

169
00:14:24,000 --> 00:14:26,000
 So if you have a Bible, you can turn there with me.

170
00:14:26,000 --> 00:14:30,000
 While you're doing that, I do think it's important to say at the outset of this series,

171
00:14:30,000 --> 00:14:35,000
 every person struggling with mental health needs God's truth.

172
00:14:35,000 --> 00:14:42,000
 But for some, your challenge is going to be more clinical or physiological than situational,

173
00:14:42,000 --> 00:14:47,000
 meaning God absolutely may choose to heal you completely,

174
00:14:47,000 --> 00:14:56,000
 but he may also use a combination of the Bible's counsel, God's truth, in pairing with medication in your life.

175
00:14:56,000 --> 00:15:02,000
 You see, in this series, I, we are going to be speaking more specifically to situational cases.

176
00:15:02,000 --> 00:15:05,000
 The reason why is I know my depth. I'm not a medical professional. I'm not a doctor.

177
00:15:05,000 --> 00:15:08,000
 I don't intend to stand on the stage and act like I am one.

178
00:15:08,000 --> 00:15:13,000
 And yet, nonetheless, whether you find yourself facing situational depression or clinical depression,

179
00:15:13,000 --> 00:15:17,000
 what you have to know is God's word is vital.

180
00:15:17,000 --> 00:15:28,000
 But if your situation is more severe, your mental health disorder is one where there is a prescription from a doctor.

181
00:15:28,000 --> 00:15:33,000
 God's word can be a really useful partner to whatever has been prescribed.

182
00:15:33,000 --> 00:15:37,000
 So with all that said, I just think that's important for us to know at the outset.

183
00:15:37,000 --> 00:15:42,000
 Now let's get into it. The goal here is I want to help you understand a new perspective on depression.

184
00:15:42,000 --> 00:15:46,000
 But before we can do that, we have to understand the problem of depression.

185
00:15:46,000 --> 00:15:49,000
 So starting in verse one, this is what it says.

186
00:15:49,000 --> 00:15:54,000
 As a deer pants for flowing streams, so pants my soul for you, O God.

187
00:15:54,000 --> 00:16:00,000
 My soul thirsts for God, for the living God. When shall I come and appear before God?

188
00:16:00,000 --> 00:16:08,000
 My tears, they've been my food day and night while they say to me all the day long, where is your God?

189
00:16:08,000 --> 00:16:12,000
 So when dealing with depression and trying to understand the problem of it,

190
00:16:12,000 --> 00:16:19,000
 the first thing you have to understand is that depression starves you of life.

191
00:16:19,000 --> 00:16:22,000
 Depression starves you of life.

192
00:16:22,000 --> 00:16:28,000
 That's what the psalmist means when he says that he is like a deer thirsting for water.

193
00:16:28,000 --> 00:16:32,000
 Notice that he doesn't say as a deer searches for water, so my soul searches for you.

194
00:16:32,000 --> 00:16:38,000
 That's not what he says. He says as a deer pants for water.

195
00:16:38,000 --> 00:16:45,000
 Why does that matter? Because it tells us the state of that animal and thus the state of our psalmist.

196
00:16:45,000 --> 00:16:51,000
 He is spiritually dehydrated. He has been deprived of life.

197
00:16:51,000 --> 00:16:58,000
 He's at a spot where he's injected the psalm with some drama because he wants God to understand.

198
00:16:58,000 --> 00:17:01,000
 I can't do this anymore. I'm at the end of my rope.

199
00:17:01,000 --> 00:17:05,000
 It feels like I don't have what it takes. Time is running out.

200
00:17:05,000 --> 00:17:12,000
 Please, God, where are you? He goes on and he says he needs not just a pool of water,

201
00:17:12,000 --> 00:17:16,000
 but flowing streams of water. Isn't that interesting? Why flowing streams?

202
00:17:16,000 --> 00:17:20,000
 Because a pool of water might satisfy him for a moment, but it's a limited resource.

203
00:17:20,000 --> 00:17:27,000
 He'll drink to the bottom of it. A flowing stream has an endless supply of life.

204
00:17:27,000 --> 00:17:32,000
 It is useful for today and tomorrow and forever. That's what he wants.

205
00:17:32,000 --> 00:17:35,000
 He knows I don't want to be in this situation anymore.

206
00:17:35,000 --> 00:17:41,000
 I have been deprived of life. I feel starved in my soul and God, give me what is needed

207
00:17:41,000 --> 00:17:47,000
 so I never have to experience this again. Do you hear it in this passage?

208
00:17:47,000 --> 00:17:53,000
 There is a starving quality to this guy's experience and there is a starving quality to depression too.

209
00:17:53,000 --> 00:17:58,000
 Like it's persistent. I was thinking it's like a marathon that you run in the snow.

210
00:17:58,000 --> 00:18:04,000
 It goes on for a really long time and the entirety of the race is miserable.

211
00:18:04,000 --> 00:18:11,000
 It numbs you out. And so you wake up day after day after day and you just sense in yourself

212
00:18:11,000 --> 00:18:15,000
 it's hard to get out of bed or the hobbies that you used to really enjoy.

213
00:18:15,000 --> 00:18:21,000
 Like you've lost interest in those things. You used to love playing pickleball or going to run club

214
00:18:21,000 --> 00:18:24,000
 or hiking through the woods and yet you don't do any of those things now

215
00:18:24,000 --> 00:18:29,000
 because you just are generally pessimistic and that actually builds on

216
00:18:29,000 --> 00:18:33,000
 because your whole attitude, your outlook on life has probably changed.

217
00:18:33,000 --> 00:18:37,000
 You see in yourself where once you were lighthearted, you'd carry casual conversation,

218
00:18:37,000 --> 00:18:44,000
 you'd crack a joke, hope it lands. Now instead you see in yourself just a negative disposition.

219
00:18:44,000 --> 00:18:53,000
 One that seems to have a perspective of gloom and despair on the day.

220
00:18:53,000 --> 00:18:59,000
 You see depression takes those things which once gave you life and it renders them lifeless.

221
00:18:59,000 --> 00:19:05,000
 That's the way it works. It starves you of life. But it doesn't just do that.

222
00:19:05,000 --> 00:19:09,000
 We got to keep understanding the problem and so as we read verse 2 it tells us a little bit more.

223
00:19:09,000 --> 00:19:13,000
 It says, "When shall I come and appear before God? My tears have been my food day and night."

224
00:19:13,000 --> 00:19:18,000
 "While they say to me all the day long, 'Where is your God?'"

225
00:19:18,000 --> 00:19:23,000
 So the second thing you need to understand if you're trying to kind of get your mind wrapped around

226
00:19:23,000 --> 00:19:28,000
 the problem of depression is that depression fills you with despair.

227
00:19:28,000 --> 00:19:33,000
 Depression fills you with despair. Meaning it doesn't just take away from you what's good.

228
00:19:33,000 --> 00:19:38,000
 It does that for sure but it also gives to you what is bad.

229
00:19:38,000 --> 00:19:45,000
 It kind of be like a cookie jar set on a shelf that's been emptied of its cookies and filled instead with spiders.

230
00:19:45,000 --> 00:19:51,000
 That's kind of what depression wants to do to you. It wants to empty out what's good and it wants to replace that with what's bad.

231
00:19:51,000 --> 00:19:56,000
 That's why the psalmist he asks himself a question. He says, "When shall I come and appear before God?"

232
00:19:56,000 --> 00:20:01,000
 That question is actually not a hopeless question.

233
00:20:01,000 --> 00:20:07,000
 You see for him, "When shall I come and appear before God?" is not a matter of if but when.

234
00:20:07,000 --> 00:20:12,000
 There's an expectation that though he feels far from God right now, God will return to him again.

235
00:20:12,000 --> 00:20:18,000
 And yet as you keep reading, you realize that in verse 3, a secondary question is asked.

236
00:20:18,000 --> 00:20:24,000
 It goes from "When" to "Where" and it's an alternative voice.

237
00:20:24,000 --> 00:20:31,000
 It's not his but someone else and as the question of "Where is your God?" is posed to the psalmist,

238
00:20:31,000 --> 00:20:35,000
 something altogether darker enters the scene.

239
00:20:35,000 --> 00:20:41,000
 Let me explain it like this. If I were to ask you, "Hey, when are your friends showing up?"

240
00:20:41,000 --> 00:20:47,000
 There's nothing offensive or moderately depressive about that question.

241
00:20:47,000 --> 00:20:51,000
 The expectation behind it is they're on their way, right? Or they're coming at some point this evening.

242
00:20:51,000 --> 00:20:55,000
 You have an expectation that they will arrive.

243
00:20:55,000 --> 00:20:59,000
 But if I ask you, "Hey, where are your friends?"

244
00:20:59,000 --> 00:21:03,000
 We move from an expectation that they'll come

245
00:21:03,000 --> 00:21:07,000
 to a question about why they're not here already.

246
00:21:07,000 --> 00:21:12,000
 Do you see that? It fills the psalmist with despair.

247
00:21:12,000 --> 00:21:17,000
 That's how depression works. It wants to fill your mind with the belief that help isn't coming.

248
00:21:17,000 --> 00:21:23,000
 There's no way out of this. I know you think a better day might arrive, but you're actually thinking wrong.

249
00:21:23,000 --> 00:21:29,000
 It's fitting in this passage that it's a different voice in the psalmist who asks the second question

250
00:21:29,000 --> 00:21:34,000
 because in our life it is often a voice of accusation,

251
00:21:34,000 --> 00:21:40,000
 the voice of an enemy that wants you to buy into the belief that help will not come.

252
00:21:40,000 --> 00:21:45,000
 When we choose to forgo the voice of truth and listen to the voice of condemnation,

253
00:21:45,000 --> 00:21:51,000
 what happens is we experience in our spirituality some sort of spiral.

254
00:21:51,000 --> 00:21:56,000
 We find ourselves indulging unhealthy behaviors. We feel down.

255
00:21:56,000 --> 00:22:00,000
 You start drinking to try to cut the edge, cope with a long day.

256
00:22:00,000 --> 00:22:05,000
 You feel down, so you find a sexual outlet, whether it's pornography or it's an old boyfriend or old girlfriend

257
00:22:05,000 --> 00:22:10,000
 or it's masturbation or sexing. You find a sexual outlet just because you want to feel something that,

258
00:22:10,000 --> 00:22:15,000
 man, it seems to be good, but in reality it's only wrong. Or you feel down, and so you binge.

259
00:22:15,000 --> 00:22:19,000
 You binge shopping. You binge eating. You binge Netflix. You binge social media.

260
00:22:19,000 --> 00:22:27,000
 You binge whatever it is that just helps you to get through today and arrive at tomorrow,

261
00:22:27,000 --> 00:22:30,000
 which raises the question, "Why do we do this kind of stuff?

262
00:22:30,000 --> 00:22:33,000
 Why do we find ourselves locked into a spiritual spiral?"

263
00:22:33,000 --> 00:22:42,000
 Well, I ask people a similar question relatively often. I'll ask them, "Why do you sin?"

264
00:22:42,000 --> 00:22:46,000
 Which always gets me an interesting response. Typically falls into one of two categories.

265
00:22:46,000 --> 00:22:52,000
 One, people will look at me and be like, "Huh? Who do you think you are asking me something like that?"

266
00:22:52,000 --> 00:22:58,000
 But the second question or the second response I'll often get is something that is super spiritual sounding.

267
00:22:58,000 --> 00:23:04,000
 People will say something along the lines of, "Well, you see, I live in the already but not yet.

268
00:23:04,000 --> 00:23:08,000
 Though sin has lost its power over me, sin still has a presence in my life."

269
00:23:08,000 --> 00:23:11,000
 And they're not wrong. They're speaking truth, like Galatians 5:17 would say,

270
00:23:11,000 --> 00:23:15,000
 "For the desires of the flesh are against the spirit. The desires of the spirit are against the flesh."

271
00:23:15,000 --> 00:23:18,000
 They're opposed to each other to keep you from doing the things that you want to do.

272
00:23:18,000 --> 00:23:23,000
 But here's the thing. When you consider, "Why do you sin?"

273
00:23:23,000 --> 00:23:32,000
 Really what I'm trying to get at is, "What is your motivation for sinning?"

274
00:23:32,000 --> 00:23:37,000
 And here's what I would say. And I'm pretty well convinced of this.

275
00:23:37,000 --> 00:23:42,000
 I've done a lot of personal study on the topic.

276
00:23:42,000 --> 00:23:47,000
 For those in Christ, and that's a really important distinction,

277
00:23:47,000 --> 00:23:57,000
 for those that have placed their faith in Jesus, you sin because you're sad.

278
00:23:57,000 --> 00:24:02,000
 And what I mean by that is this. Every one of us in life is seeking after satisfaction.

279
00:24:02,000 --> 00:24:09,000
 That's what we want most. And what we know as believers in Christ is where satisfaction is found.

280
00:24:09,000 --> 00:24:12,000
 And life to the full is found in God.

281
00:24:12,000 --> 00:24:17,000
 And yet when we seem to fall short of the satisfaction we want in Him, what do we do?

282
00:24:17,000 --> 00:24:22,000
 We seek satisfaction elsewhere, proving to the point that we are not satisfied.

283
00:24:22,000 --> 00:24:27,000
 We are in fact sad. And it's our sadness, our lack of satisfaction,

284
00:24:27,000 --> 00:24:31,000
 that drives us away from Him and into the arms of alternative love.

285
00:24:31,000 --> 00:24:34,000
 And what we feel in that experience may be a quick hit,

286
00:24:34,000 --> 00:24:39,000
 something that is fast in satisfaction, but it is not fulfilling.

287
00:24:39,000 --> 00:24:42,000
 That's why the spiral perpetuates though.

288
00:24:42,000 --> 00:24:46,000
 Because what we find ourselves is we just want a quick hit.

289
00:24:46,000 --> 00:24:51,000
 We don't want something full.

290
00:24:51,000 --> 00:24:57,000
 So many of us, we will find ourselves struggling in depressive tendencies

291
00:24:57,000 --> 00:25:01,000
 whenever we continue to indulge our sin.

292
00:25:01,000 --> 00:25:08,000
 Because what it does is it leads us not towards life, but further from life.

293
00:25:08,000 --> 00:25:13,000
 It masquerades as being the very thing we want,

294
00:25:13,000 --> 00:25:16,000
 but it never actually delivers on the promise.

295
00:25:16,000 --> 00:25:20,000
 The last thing you got to know if we want to understand the problem is in verse 4.

296
00:25:20,000 --> 00:25:22,000
 It says this, "These things I remember as I pour out my soul,

297
00:25:22,000 --> 00:25:25,000
 how I would go with a throng and lead them in procession to the house of God

298
00:25:25,000 --> 00:25:29,000
 with glad shouts and songs of praise, a multitude-keeping festival."

299
00:25:29,000 --> 00:25:33,000
 The last thing you have to understand if you want to know the problem behind depression

300
00:25:33,000 --> 00:25:37,000
 is depression isolates you from others.

301
00:25:37,000 --> 00:25:39,000
 Depression isolates you from others.

302
00:25:39,000 --> 00:25:41,000
 You can hear it in this verse.

303
00:25:41,000 --> 00:25:45,000
 He says, "I used to go with the throng to the house of God."

304
00:25:45,000 --> 00:25:47,000
 Now, you probably don't refer to your friend group as a throng.

305
00:25:47,000 --> 00:25:49,000
 Maybe you refer to them as a squad or a group.

306
00:25:49,000 --> 00:25:53,000
 But what he's saying is I used to go with my peers, my friends, my pals,

307
00:25:53,000 --> 00:25:55,000
 to the house of God.

308
00:25:55,000 --> 00:25:57,000
 And it's not just that he would go with them.

309
00:25:57,000 --> 00:25:59,000
 He even says he used to lead them,

310
00:25:59,000 --> 00:26:01,000
 which tells us something about the spiritual state of this guy.

311
00:26:01,000 --> 00:26:02,000
 He was a leader in the church.

312
00:26:02,000 --> 00:26:05,000
 He was someone that you would see in Bible study not sitting in the room

313
00:26:05,000 --> 00:26:07,000
 but sitting at the front of the room,

314
00:26:07,000 --> 00:26:09,000
 which in a roundabout way is kind of encouraging

315
00:26:09,000 --> 00:26:13,000
 because what it tells us is that you're not spiritually inferior

316
00:26:13,000 --> 00:26:15,000
 if you struggle with depression.

317
00:26:15,000 --> 00:26:19,000
 It tells us instead that you may be spiritually isolated.

318
00:26:19,000 --> 00:26:23,000
 This is exactly what happens to Elijah.

319
00:26:23,000 --> 00:26:26,000
 Like what we see in his life after he faces the prophets of Baal

320
00:26:26,000 --> 00:26:28,000
 is Jezebel threatens him.

321
00:26:28,000 --> 00:26:30,000
 She's like, "Hey, I'm going to do to you what you did to them."

322
00:26:30,000 --> 00:26:32,000
 And so he runs for his life,

323
00:26:32,000 --> 00:26:36,000
 and he is isolated from all forms of community,

324
00:26:36,000 --> 00:26:38,000
 and depression sets in.

325
00:26:38,000 --> 00:26:40,000
 So that way, the threat he thought he faced

326
00:26:40,000 --> 00:26:42,000
 is replaced by a completely different threat instead,

327
00:26:42,000 --> 00:26:45,000
 the threat known as himself.

328
00:26:45,000 --> 00:26:48,000
 1 Kings 19.4 says,

329
00:26:48,000 --> 00:26:51,000
 "But he," talking about Elijah, "himself went a day's journey into the wilderness,

330
00:26:51,000 --> 00:26:54,000
 and he came and he sat down under a broom tree,

331
00:26:54,000 --> 00:26:58,000
 and he asked that he might die, saying, 'It's enough now.

332
00:26:58,000 --> 00:27:02,000
 O Lord, take away my life, for I am no better than my fathers.'"

333
00:27:02,000 --> 00:27:05,000
 You see, there is a real danger in isolation.

334
00:27:05,000 --> 00:27:09,000
 So much so that it took a man like Elijah, a mighty prophet of God,

335
00:27:09,000 --> 00:27:12,000
 and it provoked him to consider the unimaginable.

336
00:27:12,000 --> 00:27:15,000
 It provoked him to consider ending it all.

337
00:27:15,000 --> 00:27:17,000
 Some of you, you're here,

338
00:27:17,000 --> 00:27:19,000
 and I just want to speak to you for a moment

339
00:27:19,000 --> 00:27:21,000
 because you get this space.

340
00:27:21,000 --> 00:27:25,000
 You know those thoughts because you have thought them.

341
00:27:25,000 --> 00:27:28,000
 You've prayed that prayer because you're so very tired

342
00:27:28,000 --> 00:27:31,000
 with how things are right now.

343
00:27:31,000 --> 00:27:37,000
 You, yourself, you've thought about ending it all.

344
00:27:37,000 --> 00:27:42,000
 If that's you, I want to ask you to do what Elijah did.

345
00:27:42,000 --> 00:27:45,000
 I want to ask you to choose life.

346
00:27:45,000 --> 00:27:48,000
 You see, Elijah believed what you need to believe,

347
00:27:48,000 --> 00:27:52,000
 and God is in control, and he has a beautiful plan for your life.

348
00:27:52,000 --> 00:27:56,000
 And there are people, there is a group of people here at the porch,

349
00:27:56,000 --> 00:27:59,000
 if no one else is available that wants to walk with you

350
00:27:59,000 --> 00:28:02,000
 through the valley of the shadow of death, and you need no ending,

351
00:28:02,000 --> 00:28:06,000
 it all doesn't stop the pain, it just spreads it.

352
00:28:06,000 --> 00:28:10,000
 Choose life. There is hope,

353
00:28:10,000 --> 00:28:13,000
 which is what I want to turn our attention to right now

354
00:28:13,000 --> 00:28:15,000
 because this is important.

355
00:28:15,000 --> 00:28:18,000
 Depression may be your problem,

356
00:28:18,000 --> 00:28:22,000
 but hope can be your perspective.

357
00:28:22,000 --> 00:28:25,000
 You see, we want to lead you, by God's word,

358
00:28:25,000 --> 00:28:28,000
 into a material change,

359
00:28:28,000 --> 00:28:32,000
 one where what may have been true is no longer true.

360
00:28:32,000 --> 00:28:35,000
 Instead, in your life, you've gained a new perspective

361
00:28:35,000 --> 00:28:38,000
 in place of what was once an old problem.

362
00:28:38,000 --> 00:28:41,000
 And as we read the rest of the Psalm, we're going to see how that happens.

363
00:28:41,000 --> 00:28:43,000
 So let's keep going.

364
00:28:43,000 --> 00:28:46,000
 If you want a new perspective, a perspective of hope,

365
00:28:46,000 --> 00:28:48,000
 then look at verse 6.

366
00:28:48,000 --> 00:28:51,000
 He says this, "My soul is cast down within me.

367
00:28:51,000 --> 00:28:54,000
 Therefore, I remember you from the land of Jordan

368
00:28:54,000 --> 00:28:57,000
 and of Hermon, from Mount Mazar, deep calls to deep,

369
00:28:57,000 --> 00:29:00,000
 at the roar of your waterfalls, all your breakers and your waves,

370
00:29:00,000 --> 00:29:02,000
 they've gone over me." So the first thing that you have to know

371
00:29:02,000 --> 00:29:06,000
 if you want a perspective of hope is that hope admits when things are not okay.

372
00:29:06,000 --> 00:29:08,000
 Hope admits when things are not okay.

373
00:29:08,000 --> 00:29:10,000
 That's what the psalmist is saying here.

374
00:29:10,000 --> 00:29:12,000
 He acknowledges that things are not okay.

375
00:29:12,000 --> 00:29:15,000
 He says, "Hey, my soul is cast down within me.

376
00:29:15,000 --> 00:29:18,000
 Therefore, I remember you."

377
00:29:18,000 --> 00:29:23,000
 Do you see it? He feels his feelings and he brings them to God.

378
00:29:23,000 --> 00:29:26,000
 He doesn't put on a strong face and act like everything's okay.

379
00:29:26,000 --> 00:29:28,000
 He doesn't laugh to keep from crying.

380
00:29:28,000 --> 00:29:31,000
 He doesn't pull himself up by his spiritual bootstraps

381
00:29:31,000 --> 00:29:33,000
 because he's a good soldier in the Lord's army.

382
00:29:33,000 --> 00:29:34,000
 That's not what he does.

383
00:29:34,000 --> 00:29:38,000
 Instead, he just admits honestly how he's doing.

384
00:29:38,000 --> 00:29:42,000
 And I love that it says he does so from the land of Jordan and Hermon,

385
00:29:42,000 --> 00:29:44,000
 from Mount Mazar.

386
00:29:44,000 --> 00:29:50,000
 You see, he's referencing that area of the land of Israel

387
00:29:50,000 --> 00:29:54,000
 that was furthest from the house of God.

388
00:29:54,000 --> 00:29:58,000
 Mount Hermon was the northernmost boundary marker

389
00:29:58,000 --> 00:30:04,000
 for the nation of Israel when they came to conquer the land of Canaan.

390
00:30:04,000 --> 00:30:10,000
 And so he's saying, "God, I am as far away from you as humanly possible,

391
00:30:10,000 --> 00:30:14,000
 and yet I will still remember you.

392
00:30:14,000 --> 00:30:17,000
 I will still seek you and believe the fact that you will come for me."

393
00:30:17,000 --> 00:30:19,000
 What's the point of it?

394
00:30:19,000 --> 00:30:24,000
 He knows, and we need to, that it's hard to be honest,

395
00:30:24,000 --> 00:30:26,000
 but it doesn't matter how far off you feel.

396
00:30:26,000 --> 00:30:28,000
 You need still be honest.

397
00:30:28,000 --> 00:30:30,000
 Now, this is crazy because we do this with one another.

398
00:30:30,000 --> 00:30:32,000
 People walk up and be like, "Hey, man, how you doing?"

399
00:30:32,000 --> 00:30:34,000
 I'm doing great.

400
00:30:34,000 --> 00:30:36,000
 And you're actually not doing great.

401
00:30:36,000 --> 00:30:38,000
 You're kind of suffering. You're smothered.

402
00:30:38,000 --> 00:30:40,000
 You're drowning in something.

403
00:30:40,000 --> 00:30:42,000
 It's hard to be honest with one another.

404
00:30:42,000 --> 00:30:44,000
 But here's the thing, and I want to speak to a different subset

405
00:30:44,000 --> 00:30:48,000
 because I often think that while it is difficult to be honest with others,

406
00:30:48,000 --> 00:30:51,000
 it's often more difficult to be honest with God.

407
00:30:51,000 --> 00:30:53,000
 Why is that?

408
00:30:53,000 --> 00:30:57,000
 Because we're too smart for our own good.

409
00:30:57,000 --> 00:30:59,000
 I think we're too smart for our own good.

410
00:30:59,000 --> 00:31:02,000
 Rather than admit to God how we're actually doing,

411
00:31:02,000 --> 00:31:06,000
 what we often do is we prematurely apply the truths we know

412
00:31:06,000 --> 00:31:09,000
 before we even finish praying the prayer we're trying to pray.

413
00:31:09,000 --> 00:31:11,000
 It's kind of like autocorrect.

414
00:31:11,000 --> 00:31:13,000
 I know in my phone, like when I first got it,

415
00:31:13,000 --> 00:31:16,000
 I would type my name, Kyle, and K-Y-L-E-N,

416
00:31:16,000 --> 00:31:18,000
 and every time it would autocorrect to Kyle,

417
00:31:18,000 --> 00:31:20,000
 "That's not my name!"

418
00:31:20,000 --> 00:31:22,000
 But the phone thought it was.

419
00:31:22,000 --> 00:31:25,000
 It would autocorrect to what it assumed was right.

420
00:31:25,000 --> 00:31:29,000
 And for many of you, your prayers, they function a lot like that.

421
00:31:29,000 --> 00:31:31,000
 So rather than just admitting, like,

422
00:31:31,000 --> 00:31:34,000
 "God, I don't know why this happened in my life,"

423
00:31:34,000 --> 00:31:36,000
 you can't even get through the prayer

424
00:31:36,000 --> 00:31:39,000
 before you start to register and autocorrect.

425
00:31:39,000 --> 00:31:41,000
 Well, don't forget, though,

426
00:31:41,000 --> 00:31:45,000
 God works all things according to the good of those who love him.

427
00:31:45,000 --> 00:31:48,000
 You autocorrect your feelings with truth

428
00:31:48,000 --> 00:31:51,000
 before you even express them to the Lord.

429
00:31:51,000 --> 00:31:54,000
 Others, you'll say something like, "God, instead of processing,

430
00:31:54,000 --> 00:31:57,000
 "I'm so lonely, I'm afraid that I'm going to be single

431
00:31:57,000 --> 00:31:59,000
 "for the rest of my life."

432
00:31:59,000 --> 00:32:01,000
 You'll autocorrect in the middle of your prayer

433
00:32:01,000 --> 00:32:03,000
 to something along the lines of, "But don't forget,

434
00:32:03,000 --> 00:32:05,000
 "you're not going to be alone for the rest of your life

435
00:32:05,000 --> 00:32:07,000
 "because you have Christ and his church."

436
00:32:07,000 --> 00:32:09,000
 Others of you, you'll be praying,

437
00:32:09,000 --> 00:32:12,000
 "God, I care so much about what other people think of me."

438
00:32:12,000 --> 00:32:14,000
 But before you can even get the full prayer out,

